    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2417269851" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2417269851" />
    <a title="Ben Truong" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/77170844-ben-truong"><img alt="Ben Truong" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2417269851?book_show_action=true">Jun 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben Truong" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben Truong" href="/user/show/77170844-ben-truong">Ben Truong</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/77170844-ben-truong?shelf=picture-books">picture-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/77170844-ben-truong?shelf=retellings">retellings</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/77170844-ben-truong?shelf=childrens">childrens</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2417269851" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2939483101094462305"><i>The Three Questions</i> is a children&apos;s picture book written and illustrated by Jon J. Muth, which is a retelling of a short story of the same title by Leo Tolstoy. It&apos;s about a little boy named Nikolai who wants to the best person possible, but is often unsure if he&apos;s doing the right thing. So, he has three questions to ask: What is the best time to do things?, Who is the most important One?, and What is the right thing to do?<br/><br/>The text is rather simple and straightforward. It reads more like a fable</span>
  <span id="freeText2939483101094462305" style="display:none"><i>The Three Questions</i> is a children's picture book written and illustrated by Jon J. Muth, which is a retelling of a short story of the same title by Leo Tolstoy. It's about a little boy named Nikolai who wants to the best person possible, but is often unsure if he's doing the right thing. So, he has three questions to ask: What is the best time to do things?, Who is the most important One?, and What is the right thing to do?<br /><br />The text is rather simple and straightforward. It reads more like a fable more than a story, given that the main characters, besides the boy are talking animals. Nikolai is a wonderful charter and a boy of character. The illustrations are wonderful and enforce and compliment the text rather well.<br /><br />The premise of the book is rather straightforward. It's about a little boy who wants to improve himself, but isn't sure at how to do that. So, he asked his three friends, Sonya the Heron, Gogol the Monkey, and Pushkin the Dog, the three questions getting three different answers, but not finding the right answer for him. He ventured to find Leo the Turtle – the old wise turtle who lived atop a mountain. In the end, after helping the turtle with his daily choirs and helping a panda and her child, did he finally got his answer he was looking for – that was with him all along.<br /><br /><i>"That the most important time is right now, that the right person is the one right beside you, and the right thing to do is to help others who are standing by your side."</i><br /><br />All in all, <i>The Three Question</i> is a wonderful children's book about how to do what is right and when to do it and a wonderful retelling of Leo Tolstoy original short story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2939483101094462305" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

